land, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cralle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of English   Crawley  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of German <b>Kralle</b> (see   Krall  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Crawley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Crawley, for example in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Sussex, and Oxfordshire, named with Old English <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Crowley  .","Irish (Louth): in Ireland, this is generally the English name in 1 above, but it may also have been adopted for <b>McCrawley</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghallaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghallach</i>’, also Anglicized as <b>Magreely</b>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":4,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert de Cralle was born in 1333. He married Marie de Pepelsham in 1384, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1367, in Sussex, England, at the age of 34, and was buried in Sussex, England."},"et":{"1333–1367":"1333–1367","–Female":"Surnud","1335–1405":"1335–1405","1356–Female":"1356–Surnud","1366–1457":"1366–1457","1337":"1337","1457":"1457","1335":"1335","1367":"1367","1356":"1356","1333":"1333","1366":"1366","1453":"1453","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1405":"1405","Cralle Place, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cralle Manor, Cralle, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1333–1367":"1333–1367","–Female":"Kuollut","1335–1405":"1335–1405","1356–Female":"1356–Kuollut","1366–1457":"1366–1457","1337":"1337","1457":"1457","1335":"1335","1367":"1367","1356":"1356","1333":"1333","1366":"1366","1453":"1453","about 1356":"noin 1356","1405":"1405","Cralle Place, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cralle Manor, Cralle, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuning